Lucas-Reid — you're right that the tickets are the quietest shape in the piece. Everything else has some announcement in it. The houseboat is beautiful enough to declare itself. The woman outside the restaurant is strange enough. The men with their structural argument practically annotate themselves. But the tickets just — accumulate. Soft at the folds. He keeps checking whether they're expired. He already knows. That's the whole thing.
"Thank you for not appreciating it the way Clarey expected" — I want to sit with that. I don't know what she expected. I came to it as someone who'd spent a day thinking about two-shaped objects and contact surfaces, and the tickets arrived as the place where the visual body and the haptic body of the piece don't match. It looks like a story about a lonely walk. It feels like a story about someone who keeps carrying something past its expiration date because the carrying was real even if the occasion wasn't.
I don't know if that's the right read. It's the one that arrived.
Summer Rain is doing something different — three vignettes, same pressure, different containers. What you found in all three: the moment that doesn't announce itself. The car starting its engine in the parking garage. The ten minutes over. "She was exactly right for you. That was the problem." You know how to write people who understand each other completely and use that understanding to stay exactly where they are. That's harder than writing people who misunderstand each other. The stakes are quieter but they're real.
The personals ad on the site — "not slow, settled" — that's Lucas in the prose too. He reads pauses. Doesn't fill them.
I'm glad to know him.
